(30, 'Amazon by Abhinav Singh', '09-28-17', 'akki', 'amazon_logo_RGB.jpg', 'Amazon,interview,experience,internship', '<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:center"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">Amazon</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:center"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">Abhinav Singh</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Date : 22<sup>nd</sup> July 2016</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><u>Round 1 (Coding + MCQs) :</u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">1. 20 MCQs related to C, DBMS, Aptitude.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">2. <a href="http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/given-a-string-find-its-first-non-repeating-character/" style="color:#0563c1; text-decoration:underline">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/given-a-string-find-its-first-non-repeating-character/</a></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">3. A square matrix filled with numbers from 1 to n^2 in spiral form. Find kth element.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><u>Round 2 (Technical Interview) :</u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">1. Snake and ladder problem : <a href="http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/snake-ladder-problem-2/" style="color:#0563c1; text-decoration:underline">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/snake-ladder-problem-2/</a></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">2. Form largest number from an array of numbers : <a href="http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/given-an-array-of-numbers-arrange-the-numbers-to-form-the-biggest-number/" style="color:#0563c1; text-decoration:underline">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/given-an-array-of-numbers-arrange-the-numbers-to-form-the-biggest-number/</a></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><u>Round 3 (Technical Interview) :</u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">1. Collect maximum coins in a matrix : <a href="http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/collect-maximum-coins-before-hitting-a-dead-end/" style="color:#0563c1; text-decoration:underline">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/collect-maximum-coins-before-hitting-a-dead-end/</a></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">2. Building bridges : <a href="http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/dynamic-programming-set-14-variations-of-lis/" style="color:#0563c1; text-decoration:underline">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/dynamic-programming-set-14-variations-of-lis/</a></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">3. Print linked list in reverse form : <a href="http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/write-a-recursive-function-to-print-reverse-of-a-linked-list/" style="color:#0563c1; text-decoration:underline">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/write-a-recursive-function-to-print-reverse-of-a-linked-list/</a></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">4. Then we talked about the double century of Virat Kohli against WI that he completed the same day (Probably the only part of interview which was not covered in &ldquo;geeksforgeeks&rdquo; :P).</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><u>Round 4 (Technical Interview) :</u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">1. Merge k sorted arrays : <a href="http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/merge-k-sorted-arrays/" style="color:#0563c1; text-decoration:underline">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/merge-k-sorted-arrays/</a></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">2. Find all paths in binary tree with given sum : <a href="http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/root-to-leaf-path-sum-equal-to-a-given-number/" style="color:#0563c1; text-decoration:underline">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/root-to-leaf-path-sum-equal-to-a-given-number/</a> (with a slight modification that the path can end on a non-leaf node as well)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><u>Round 5 (Telephonic Technical Interview) :</u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">This interview NEVER took place&nbsp;</span></span>.</p>\r\n'),
(31, 'Walmart Labs by Apoorva', '09-28-17', 'akki', 'walmartlabs-logo.jpg', 'Walmart,Walmart Labs,interview,experience,internship', '<p><strong>INTERVIEW EXPERIENCE</strong><br />\r\n<strong>Company Name</strong>: Walmart Labs<br />\r\n<strong>Name:</strong> Apoorva<br />\r\n<strong>Branch:</strong> Information Technology<br />\r\nCPI: 9.22<br />\r\n<strong>Coding Round</strong><br />\r\n3 coding questions.<br />\r\n1. n cities connected as a ring. Find number of ways to reach destination from source with exactly k moves. (30 Points)<br />\r\n2. n rows, each row has different number of seats, cost of a seat is number of seats left in that row. Find maximum profit that can be gained. (30 Points)<br />\r\n3. n vacation days given. 4 possibilities : 0 &ndash; yoga camp is closed, coding contest is off, 1 &ndash; yoga camp is open, coding contest is off, 2 &ndash; yoga camp is closed, coding contest is on, 4 &ndash; both open. Now on a day, we can either do yoga (if yoga camp is open), or we can give coding contest (if contest is open) , or we can REST. If on a day yoga was done, we cannot do yoga on the next day. Find minimum possible number of REST days (Dynamic Programming). (40 Points)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>1st Technical Round</strong><br />\r\nInterviewer was quite friendly. He asked me to refer to him by his name.<br />\r\nHe asked me to introduce myself technically. Then I told him about what technical skills I know and about my project.<br />\r\nMy AOI was networking so he asked me to explain the OSI model. I was telling him about the application layer, when he told me to stop and he asked me another ques.<br />\r\nHe gave me a question to check whether the left subtree is the mirror of right subtree or not. He asked me to write the code.<br />\r\nHe then asked me another ques it was like a root node of the tree is given and one leaf node is given and you have to arrange the tree such that given leaf node will become root node. (He was quite happy with my approach.)<br />\r\nThen he gave me one design problem. How will u implement ctrl +f feature on a pdf or any other doc. I told him brute force one by one search. Then he asked to improve it. Then I told him the KMP algorithm. He told me to think another data structure. Then I told him using a trie.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2nd Technical Round</strong><br />\r\nHe asked me to introduce myself.<br />\r\nHe gave me to write code to find powerset of given array.<br />\r\nHe asked me another ques that we have been given two strings and we have to check whether one string is rotation of another or not. (http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/a-program-to-check-if-strings-are-rotations-of-each-other/)<br />\r\nHe gave me one another question in which suppose a string like &lsquo;My name is Apoorva&rsquo; is given and I have to reverse the string in o(n) time complexity and o(1) space complexity.<br />\r\nHe asked me the difference between 32-bit processor and 64- bit processor and 32 bit CPU and 64-bit CPU and 32-bit processor and 32-bit CPU.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3rd Technical Round</strong><br />\r\nHe asked me to introduce myself.<br />\r\nHe asked me to swap variables without using temp variable.<br />\r\nHe asked me diff between mutex and semaphore.<br />\r\nHe asked me application of pointer to function.<br />\r\nSome more basic questions of OS and DBMS were asked.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>HR Round</strong><br />\r\nHe asked me to introduce myself.<br />\r\nHe gave me his laptop and opened the MakeMyTrip website and asked me what else can MakeMyTrip provide to increase its customers. I told him door to door taxi service and flight or train information by sms, whether it is late or not and food services.<br />\r\nHe asked me why I wanted to join Walmart Labs.<br />\r\nThen he told me your pointer is good and you have good knowledge then why won&rsquo;t u go for higher studies.<br />\r\nThen he asked me one bad thing about MNNIT.<br />\r\nAfter 4 rounds of interviews, I was finally selected!&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),
(32, 'Walmart Labs by Akash Agarwal', '09-28-17', 'akki', 'walmartlabs-logo.jpg', 'Walmart,Walmart Labs,interview,experience,internship', '<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">&nbsp;<span style="font-size:11.0pt">Name: Akash Agarwal </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Company: Walmart Labs </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">CTC offered: 18.57 LPA </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Coding Round: </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">This round was conducted on Hackerearth platform. It consisted of 3 coding questions out of which two were related to Dynamic Programming and one was adhoc. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">I was able to solve two of them and was shortlisted for the interviews. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Round 1 (F2F Interview): </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">This round started with a brief introduction. She then asked me about my favourite subject and why that was my favourite. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">She then moved on to some coding questions. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">1. You are given an array on which three operations were allowed- </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Get(i): </span></strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">It returns the value at index i </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Length(): </span></strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">It returns the length of the array </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Reverse(i,j): </span></strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">It reverses the array from index I to index j. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">You have to sort the array. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Solution: </span></strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Bubble Sort </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">2. http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/construct-a-special-tree-from-given-preorder-traversal/ </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">3. You are given a function <strong>isValid(string s) </strong>which returns true if the string s exists in dictionary </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">and a string. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">You have to count the number of strings that can be formed from the given string and that are valid i.e. they exist in the dictionary. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">E.g.: Given string: TEA </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">TEA- valid </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">TAE- invalid </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">ATE- valid </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">AET- invalid </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">EAT- valid </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">ETA- invalid </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Ans: 3 </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Solution: </span></strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Generate all the permutations of a string using backtracking(Brute Force Approach). </span></span></sp