(38, 'Oracle by Prashant Khulbe', '09-28-17', 'akki', 'oracle-1.jpg', 'oracle,interview,experience,internship', '<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">Name: </span></span></strong><span style="color:black">Prashant Khulbe</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">Company: </span></span></strong><span style="color:black">Oracle</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">Location: </span></span></strong><span style="color:black">Bangalore/Hyderabad</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">CTC: </span></span></strong><span style="color:black">22 LPA</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">Selected for the profile: </span></span></strong><span style="color:black">Application Engineer</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">Written Round:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">The written round was conducted on oracle&rsquo;s platform and the duration was 122 minutes precisely.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">It consisted of mcq&rsquo;s on 4 major areas &ndash; Software aptitude, English, coding skills, technical skills (like</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">OS, DBMS, OOAD,CN). The 4 sections were further subdivided into 4-5 smaller sections containing 7-</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">8 questions each and each subsection had a time limit of around 8-10 minutes. There was only fwd</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">scrolling ( so once you skipped a question, you would have to traverse till the end and then loop</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">back). Also once marked, you cannot change your answer for the question. There was nothing</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">mentioned about negative marking.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">Around 65 students were shortlisted for each of the 2 profiles (server tech being the other profile)</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">out of 355 students.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">F2F Interview 1 (Technical)(45 min):</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">Due to large number of candidates shortlisted for interviews, each interviewer was handling 2-3</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">candidates simultaneously . He directly fired different coding questions on us without wasting even a</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">second. I was given to implement next_permutation() function of c++ and the other student was</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">asked about the excel sheet problem </span><span style="color:blue">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/find-excel-column-name-givennumber/</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">After this round I was told to wait outside. Another interviewer was present there and he quickly</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">asked me 2 more coding questions </span><span style="color:blue">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/a-product-array-puzzle/ </span><span style="color:black">and the</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">other question was - given a paragraph find which alphabet doesn&rsquo;t occur in it. The key to this round</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">was to give simple, quick and optimal solution wrt time and space. A normal solution led to direct</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">exit from this round without any deliberations.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">F2F Interview 2 (Technical) (2 hr):</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">The same interviewer took me in for the next round. In this round he was even more strict and</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">direct. He first asked me about the manhole puzzle, I started giving him the solutions that i knew</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">but he refused to agree to any of them, finally after 7-8 possible solutions he changed the question</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">saying that all solutions were wrong. Then he told me to design a database that could calculate and</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">predict using queries the finishing date of a project assigned to me. (given to me was list of jobs</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">involved in the project ,their dependencies and time taken to complete each job ). Again he started</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">refuting all my solutions and indirectly stressed that I better give the correct solution or exit !!! Then</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">finally after 1.5 hrs he agreed to my solution. He revealed that he was satisfied with all my solutions</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">from the start. (so basically it was kind of a stress interview and he wanted to see how many</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">solutions can I come up with).</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">F2F Interview 3 (Managerial) (75 min):</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">After the second interview I was called in for the managerial round that was taken by the senior</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">most Interviewer of the panel. He was very friendly and helpful and started a general discussion</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">about me, my hometown, family etc. Then he moved on to my resume and went through it line by</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">line , cross-questioning me at every stage about my school, achievements, projects etc in detail.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">After this he asked me some technical questions about normalization with examples. Then he asked</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">me Why Oracle ? and why this profile? There were some questions from the PPT as well !!! Then he</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">gave me a design question in which I had to make screen shots of an app for Library management ,</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">covering all aspects and details. I also had to make the back end tables in a normalized manner along</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">with the functional dependencies. I continued for about 45-50 minutes and he was satisfied by my</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">solution. In the end he asked if I had any questions and I asked 2-3 questions. He then recommended</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">me for HR round.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">F2F Interview 4 (HR) (20-25 min):</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">The HR lady was neither friendly nor strict. She started by asking about my background, my family,</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">hobbies etc. Then she asked Why oracle? She also aked about my location preference and the</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">reason behind it. This was followed by a character test where she enquired about my strength and</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">weakness.I was again asked some questions from the PPT !!! In the end she asked if I had any</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">questions for her and I as ked 3-4 questions.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">So, that was it. After 5-6 hrs of unending wait I got the good news...</span></span></span></p>\r\n'),
(39, 'Citrix by Manas Srivastava', '09-28-17', 'akki', 'citrix.jpg', 'citrix,interview,experience,internship', '<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">&nbsp;<strong><span style="font-size:28.0pt">Citrix Systems Interview Experience: </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">Job Profile: </span></strong><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Citrix Systems offered 2 profiles in our college- Software Dev and Software Dev-Test </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">CTC: </span></strong><span style="font-size:11.5pt">18.52 LPA (12.05 lacs in hand + 4 lacs signing bonus over a period of 3 years + other benefits). This was same for both the profiles. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">Round 1: </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">The first round was an online round conducted on hackerrank platform. It had 2 tests- </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">(i) The first test consisted of 50 MCQs to be solved in 60 minutes. There was no negative marking. The MCQs covered all core subjects of Computer Science- C/C++,Data Structures, Algorithms, DBMS, OOPs, Operating Systems and Networking. It also included 4-6 aptitude questions which were of moderate level. This round is easy to clear if your fundamentals are strong. Time won&rsquo;t be a problem. Just be calm and you can easily attempt all questions. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">(ii) The second test was a coding round. There were 2 questions to be solved in 60 minutes. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">a.) Given an array, you need to find that position in the array such that sum of elements on its left side is equal to the sum of elements on the right. It was given that such a position always existed in the input array. For e.g.: </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">INPUT: 2 5 3 1 6 4 </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">OUTPUT: 4 </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Explanation: The 4</span><span style="font-size:8.0pt">th </span><span style="font-size:11.5pt">number in the array is 1. Elements to its left are 2, 5 and 3 (sum=10) and elements to its right are 6 and 4 (sum=10). </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">b.) Given a list of numbers, you need to group these numbers such that each group has numbers that are anagrams of each other. Then we had to return a list of these numbers such that each group was sorted and the groups were also sorted among each other. Groups were sorted according to the first element of each group. For e.g.: </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">INPUT: 23 172 1143 32 3141 29 92 271 127 1314 </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">OUTPUT: 23 32 29 92 127 172 271 1143 1314 3141 </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Explanation: For the input, following groups will be formed- {23,32}, {127,172,271}, {1143,1314,3141} and {29,92}. Elements in these groups were sorted and now all the groups were sorted among each other according to their first element, that is, the group {29,92} will come before the group {127,172,271} because 29&lt;127. So now the order is as follows- {23,32} , {29,92}, {127,172,271}, {1143,1314,3141}. Finally a single list had to be returned in this order. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Hints: The first question can be solved by making a cumulative array from the given array. The modified array will be such that each element will store the sum of elements of original array up to that index. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">The second question can be solved using map. Store the numbers as strings and sort each number. If two numbers are anagrams of each other, than after sorting they will be same. Each time you find a new sorted order, add it as a new key in the map. Let the value of each key be a vector. If a sorted order is already present in the map, simply add that number to the vector of that key. Look out for corner cases. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">33 people were shortlisted after this round for interviews. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">INTERVIEW ROUNDS </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Citrix had a very thorough interview process. Every candidate&rsquo;s profile had been maintained which included his/her resume, printouts of the code that had been submitted on hackerrank during online coding round. Also we had been marked on certain aspects based on our resume and Online test on hackerrank. This was done by them to categorize us into the 2 profiles. Some of us were being evaluated for Developer role and some for Dev-Test role. This was not a strict categorization, but just an initial evaluation. The profile could change based on interviews. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">Technical Interview 1: </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">The interviewer asked me to introduce myself. I gave my introduction and told him about my project. He listened carefully and asked some basic questions but he was not much interested as the project pertained to human detection technology using machine learning and it was of basically no use at Citrix. He then turned over my profile and asked me the approach I used to solve the anagram question from coding round. He changed the question and asked me to write code if the input was strings and not numbers. He told me that uppercase and lowercase characters must be treated equally and the code must be written in C and not in C++ so that I do not use STL. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Then he asked me to write code for reversing a linked list. I did it using iterative method. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Further questions were from OS. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">-Define critical section. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">-What is deadlock? </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">-What are conditions for deadlock? </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">-Write a code that explains deadlock. I did not write code but diagrammatically explained him the concept of circular wait. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">There was ample discussion on every answer that I gave. Please choose your words carefully while defining simple concepts. If you say something absurd, the interviewer can easily pick that up and use it against you. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">Technical Interview 2: </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">This was the toughest round. The interviewer told me to introduce myself. He asked me what my favorite subjects are. I answered Data Structures, Algorithms and Operating Systems. But he was looking for Networking and so he asked me if I was comfortable with it. I told him honestly that I liked Networking when I studied it in 5th semester but I had not revised it recently and so I didn&rsquo;t remember many concepts. The interviewer was very kind. He calmed me down and told me that he understood and it was OK that I had not revised Networking. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">He then asked me, if given a choice of profiles, which one would I prefer. I said developer and he asked me why not tester. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Then he asked me to design the backend system for IRCTC. I suppose he asked this because I chose developer profile. He asked me about data structures that I will use and how would I implement all the functionalities. He gave hints and this lasted for about 35 -40 minutes. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Then he asked me whether I had any experience in mobile app or web development. I said no and told him that I have dedicated most of my free time to machine learning and artificial intelligence. I had to convince him that even if I had no experience with web or app platforms, I could still use my skills for development role. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">He then asked me the programming languages I was comfortable in. I told him I was equally good in C, C++ and Java. He then told me to write an Object Oriented code in C++ for Chess game. He wanted me to design an application similar to that present in computers for chess game. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">After this, he asked me what I would do if I had a C code in which a certain variable was being used several times and I had to decrease its access time. I told him that we need to use &ldquo;register&rdquo; keyword and then I explained him its working and how the compiler deals with it. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Next he asked me about function pointers. Give a real life example where function pointers are useful. He then asked where does C++ use function pointers for its internal working. I told him about virtual functions in C++ and how it handles runtime polymorphism using vtables and vptrs and that vtables actually store pointers to functions. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">Technical Interview 3: </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Again the same question asking my introduction. He started with OS questions. Difference between process and thread. He told me to explain conceptually and not give a bookish answer. In my personal opinion, never say &ldquo;Thread is a lightweight process&rdquo; and stop. Always try to explain how and why it is a lightweight process. He was impressed by my answer. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">He then told me to name and explain all scheduling techniques that I am aware of. I started by explaining him FIFO and he asked me its drawback. I told starvation. He then asked me how can it be improved. So I explained him Round Robin method. I wanted to further explain him SJF, SRTF and Real Time Scheduling Algorithms but he stopped me. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">He then switched to DS and Algo. He asked me to write code to reverse linked list. I told him that I had already answered the same question in the first round. He turned over my profile to check and it was there. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Next he told me to write code for checking whether there exists a loop in singly linked list. I told him the fast pointer and slow pointer approach. He then extended the question to finding the starting point of the loop. I told the solution (It is there on geeksforgeeks). He then told me to explain and mathematically prove that how this fast pointer-slow pointer approach works for this problem. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">He then gave me a puzzle. There is a biased coin and we only know that it is biased and not that on which side it is biased or by how much. We have to execute a fair match from this coin. I could not answer this puzzle. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Finally he asked me the solution for the Maximum Sum Subarray problem. I told him about Kadane&rsquo;s Algorithm and its assumption, but he wanted me to write code for the Divide and Conquer approach. I told him that Kadane is more efficient but he insisted on divide and conquer method and wanted to see how I approached it. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">Then he asked me if I had any questions for him. Never say that you don&rsquo;t have any questions. Always try to ask some logical questions about the company. This shows that you are interested and serious about the company. You can ask about particular products of the company, work culture, etc. I asked him 2 questions </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">HR Round: </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">This was the final round. He started a timer and asked me to introduce myself for complete 1 minute. Then normal HR questions followed- strengths, weaknesses, family background. He then asked me what type of work I would prefer. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">He also asked me whether I had any questions. I asked him about how freshers are inducted into respective teams at Citrix. He explained the entire induction program to me, beginning from joining and right up to allocation of teams. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">It was a long interview process and finally after 13 hours of struggle, I was offered the job </span><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">J </span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:16.0pt">KEY POINTS: </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">1. Citrix Systems is a company that tests all your CS fundamentals and especially Networking. I was lucky that I was able to convince them about how I was not in touch with Networking and that is why I think that networking questions were not asked from me. But a lot of my friends were tested on Networking very deeply. I got through because I chose OS and could answer all OS questions. My advice would be that if you are going for Citrix, do strengthen your Networking concepts. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">2. Never say no when the interviewer asks you if you have any questions for them. That gives a bad impression. This surely doesn&rsquo;t mean, that you ask anything that comes to your mind. Whenever you are about to give interview for a company, do prepare some logical questions beforehand because these questions are almost always asked. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">3. In all my rounds, I was asked to introduce myself. Be prepared with an introduction of yourself. If possible, practice it so that you don&rsquo;t stammer in front of the interviewer. Remember, this is your first impression on the interviewer and you want it to go well because it would not only give you confidence but also create a positive vibe in the interview room. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">4. Be thorough with your projects and subjects that you list as &ldquo;Area of Interest&rdquo;. It gives a very bad impression if you perform poorly in an area which you consider to be your strength. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:11.5pt">5. The interviewers were very kind and helpful. They gave me hints if I got stuck somewhere. They were not looking for bookish answers but were interested in whether I knew the concepts. They were not looking for exact solutions but observing the line of thought I followed to tackle a particular problem. So it&rsquo;s always better to think aloud and keep telling the interviewer what you are thinking and how you want to approach the problem.</span></span></span></p>\r\n');
INSERT INTO `cmsposts` (`post_id`, `post_title`, `post_date`, `post_author`, `post_image`, `post_keywords`, `post_content`) VALUES
(40, 'Citrix by Ashish Kumar', '09-28-17', 'akki', 'citrix.jpg', 'citrix,interview,experience,internship', '<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black">&nbsp;<strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Name : Ashish Kumar </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Company : Citrix R &amp; D </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Location : Banglore </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">CTC : 18.52 LPA </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Profile : Software Developer </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Written Round : </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Conducted on Hackerrank </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">1. 50 MCQ mostly on OS, Networking,DS,Algo, OOP , Aptitude, C/C++ Output. No of question on aptitude and networks were less however C,C++, DS, Algo, OOP have lot of weightage. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">(Citrix counts scores for each section and marks distribution is passed as reference to interviewer so you should take care of each section and total attempts ) </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">2. Coding round: </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">2 Question in 1 Hour </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Find the smallest index of an element in an array such that sum of elements left to index is equal to sum of elements right to index. If no such index is found return -1. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">You can do it easily using partial sum in O(n). </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Given numbers in a array group the anagram numbers such that individual groups are sorted and all groups are sorted according to smallest element in group. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Assume Given array is {51,15,128,821,281} output will be {15,51,128,281,821} </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Sort the element first using STL and then group it into anagrams to get sorted sequence. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Citrix decides cutoff for each section (may be also for subsection in MCQ) take care of it. </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Interview Round 1 </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Interviewer asked me to introduce myself and quickly describe the work/activities done after getting into college. After that lot of questions as written below </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> detect and remove loop in link list with proper corner cases </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> code to get middle element in link list </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> get nth largest element in BST without using extra space and in O(n) . ( I used static variable and recursive function call ) </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Get median in a stream of input data. I explained it using AVL but he was expecting solution based on min and max heap (Standard Question see it on geeksforgeeks ) </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Difference between mutex and binary semaphore in which case which one is used. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Conditions for deadlock and deadlock removal method </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Asked about knowledge of Hashmap in java I explained it using key,value pair and then told me to implement Hashmap , I implemented it using Hash function and Linked List Chaining (for solving collision problems) He was not satisfied with linked list chaining and asked what will happen if all data collide with same hash value. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">(Even though Linked List Chaining is correct solution, the improved solution is using balance trees, in case of collision when link list size increase after certain factor trees are used instead of link list) </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">(Trees implementation for handling collision is implemented in JAVA 8 which is most updated version ,so be prepared for this type of questions ) </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">1 Puzzle </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">1.you have 1 biased coin ( You don&rsquo;t know head biased or tail biased ) you have to make a fair toss using that biased coin. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Then he asked about interested profile ( Dev/Dev-test) and area ( App/Networking/iOS) , I preferred Dev ( Networking) and asked some questions related to profile and technology getting used. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Round 2 Interview </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Primarily Focused on Networking concepts </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Asked everything in networking including OSI layer, different protocols in TCP/IP layer, Media Access Control and Routing, Broadcast and unicast, DHCP, TCP, Flow control, Fragmentation, Congestion Control ,Window Size, Various Algorithm for Congestion Control. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Then told me to describe some network attacks, I described ( man in the middle, Flood Attack ,Session Hijacking ). Asked me to describe SYN attack and its prevention and details about syn cookies. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">3 Puzzles </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Given a cube of 4 x 4 x 4 and all side painted Red tell me the no of Pieces with 3 side painted ,2 side painted, 1 side painted and no side painted if cube is divided into 1 x 1 x 1 smaller cubes. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">(Easy one just Visualization) </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> No of minimum weighing required to get defective piece from 8 balls. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Message Exchange puzzle when locks and keys are with same person and you need to transfer a message in a box using locks from one person to another person with the help of intruder who can see you message if box is left opened during transfer. (Google for it you will get complete question) </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Round 3 Tech Interview </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Write code for getting intersection point in link list , reduce the time complexity when it is given that link list is sorted, describe worst case and order of algorithm. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Size of primitive datatypes, pointers in c++ for different architecture 32/64 bit. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> OOP concepts, dynamic polymorphism, Garbage Collection in java /C++ ,Algorithm for garbage collection, </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Round 4 : Managerial </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Describe yourself, Weakness, Strength. Why Citrix and some traditional HR Questions. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Describe you Project work and its application what you have done in that and how your contribution helped in getting final results, How you can say that you are a Team Player. (My Project focuses on HADOOP and DHT so I described Bigdata concepts, MapReduce and implementation of MapReduce on peer to peer networks.) </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Round 5 : Tech Interview </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Given two strings such that lowercase and uppercase alphabet and considered indistinguishable check whether they are anagrams or not without using extra space and &lt; ,&gt; operator. I used == and || operator to get the answer </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Given char *c=&rdquo;citrix&rdquo;; difference between printf( &ldquo;%s&rdquo; ,(*c)++); and printf(&ldquo;%s&rdquo;,*(c++)); </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Asked me Do you have any Question and I replied with &ldquo;No&rdquo; (I had been already exhausted); </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt">Points to care </span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Take care of your cutoff in written rounds </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Ask question even if you don&rsquo;t have any or you don&rsquo;t want to ask.(Frame some good questions beforehand) </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:11.0pt"> Focus more on Networking /C++/Algo and DS </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),
(41, 'Citrix by Anurag Agnihotri', '09-28-17', 'akki', 'citrix.jpg', 'citrix,interview,experience,internship', '<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Name: Anugrah Agnihotri</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Company: Citrix</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Location: Bangalore</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">CTC: 18.52 LPA</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Selected for the profile: Software Developer</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif">Written Round:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">The written round (conducted on HackerRank) consisted of two sections:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">1. First section consisted of 50 MCQs to be attempted in 1 hour.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">The questions covered almost all the topics including Networking, OS, C/C++ output, OOP,</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">quantitative aptitude.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">2. This section consisted of 2 programming questions to be solved in 1 hour :</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">a. Find a pivot index in an array of integers such that the sum of elements to the left of</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">the pivot is equal to the sum on the right. Could be easily done in O(n).</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">b. Given an array of integers. Arrange this array in such a way that all anagrams are</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">grouped together and the groups themselves are sorted on the basis of the first</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">element of each group. Eg- Input: 981, 27, 819, 72,198. Output: 27, 72,198,891,981.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">My code worked only for some of the test cases.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">33 students were shortlisted for further rounds.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif">Interview Round 1 (Duration 1hr 15 mins)</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">The interview started out with the obvious- &ldquo;Tell me about yourself&rdquo;. I spoke briefly about my</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">projects and extra-curricular activities.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">I was then asked about networking in detail, which covered almost all the layers. I had to speak at</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">length about DNS and the differences between a router and a switch. Packet format etc. where also</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">discussed.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Make sure your networking concepts are very strong. A couple of tricky questions were asked &ndash;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">&ldquo;How does the server respond to a client&rsquo;s message addressed to a port which is not open? Explain</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">for both TCP and UDP.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">He then moved on to algorithms. A simple question on finding prime numbers in a given range was</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">asked. I coded the solution on paper and did a dry run. He asked me the complexity of the code and</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">various complexity notations in general.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">The last question he asked me was to find out the number of matches to be played between teams</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">in the case when each team plays the other and also in the case when a tournament tree is formed.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">24 candidates were shortlisted for the next round.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif">Interview Round 2 (Duration 1hr 30 minutes)</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">The interviewer was friendly but seemed to be in a hurry.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Questions were asked on the complexities and applications of heap and queues.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">How will you find the median in a stream of integers? (I implemented it using two heaps.)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Which sorting algo would you preferably use? (I spoke about Timsort of Java.)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">When does the worst case complexity of quick sort arise?</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">How does randomized quicksort help?</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">He then moved onto hashing. Explain why it is done.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">He asked me to design a hashtable from scratch. (I did it using arrayList/vectors and linked list of a</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">custom Node class objects for handling collisions.)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">I also spoke about load factor, double hashing etc.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">He then asked me to design a LinkedHashMap using the concepts of inheritance, given a HashMap as</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">the parent class. (The interviewer helped me out with hints when I was stuck.)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Algo: Number of ways of dividing a number recursively as n/2,n/3,n/5. I gave a DP solution &ndash; similar</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">to the coin change problem.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Last question was a puzzle &ndash; 10 coins are placed on a table. Some have their heads up while others</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">have their tails up. You are blindfolded. Divide the coins into 2 groups containing the same number</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">of heads and tails each.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri,Bold&quot;,sans-serif">Interview Round 3(Duration 1 hr)</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">This was a managerial round taken by a senior member of the hiring team.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">The interview was heavily focused on Android App Development and my projects.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">I spoke at length about 2 of my apps on the Play Store, demonstrating their functionalities to the</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">interviewer.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Features such as Push notification, leaderboards, GPS, widgets etc were discussed. (Not the</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">technical aspects of them.)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Questions like what other features do you have in the pipeline? Why Android? Are you willing to</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">work on iOS? Where is the future of mobile tech heading? Can cryptography be used in some</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">upcoming apps?</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">He then asked me about my schooling and family background. Questions were asked about my</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">extra-curricular activities &ndash; Srijan, Enactus, quizzing etc.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">I then asked him a few questions regarding Citrix and the kind of work they do.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">After a wait of 2-3 hours, the results were announced. I was lucky enough to be one of the ten</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">candidates selected!</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Some learnings from my own experience that I would like to share:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-family:Symbol">&middot; </span>Make sure you are good with algorithms and data structures. Speed and correctness both</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">are essential. LeetCode and InterviewBit are two amazing resources &ndash; and ofcourse</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">GeeksforGeeks has an exhaustive collection of questions and interview experiences.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-family:Symbol">&middot; </span>Try to have atleast 1 good project (Android/Web Development/Machine Learning/any topic</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">of your liking) by the end of 3<span style="font-size:7.0pt">rd </span>year. You can clear some rounds simply by impressing the</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">interviewer with a good project.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-family:Symbol">&middot; </span>Last but not the least, have faith in your abilities. Remember, sometimes you win,</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">sometimes you lose learn!</span></span></p>\r\n'),
(42, 'Citi by Anjam', '09-28-17', 'akki', '1200px-Citi.svg.png', 'citi,interview,experience,internship', '<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><u>A written test was conducted </u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Pattern : </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Aptitude (quants) &ndash; questions were from domains ranging from time and work , train problem . they were easy but you couldn&rsquo;t go back to those questions which you did skip.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Logical reasoning &ndash; some dice related problem , figure relating skills were checked. It was very easy and there&rsquo;s no need to&nbsp; worry about it.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">C/C++ concept &ndash; oops concept, o/p related questions ,3-5 from os and 2-4 from networking.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Coding round (short listing was not done on this basis) </span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><u>Technical interview </u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Questions to me were :</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>tell me about yourself.</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Uses of normalization forms , explain nf&rsquo;s in detail. ( i explained all the anomalies and explained with an example of student table) </strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Relate data abstraction to real life.( i gave an example of a bus ).</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Polymorphism,&nbsp; and its relevance in c++ .</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>My project and my role in that. (i am from electrical but i emphasized on the fact that coding part for the same was handled by me ). </strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Why citi and why software (considering my electrical background)</strong></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0.5in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong><u>Hr interview</u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Tell me something about Citicorp.</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Your area of improvement according to you.</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Your 3 strengths and weaknesses.</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Why engineering?</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Why not core (your cpi is good) and why software?</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>How do you relate c with your day to day life?</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Your one quality which you think lets you stand way ahead of others.</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Which of us(they were actually 2 ) do you think is from hr department. (i actually laughed at this one :p)</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Tell me one thing which you don&rsquo;t like about us.</strong></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Any questions for us.</strong></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0.5in; margin-right:0in; text-align:center">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0.5in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><em>Answer each and every questions with confidence .questions like relate with real life were to actually test ours analogical skills . </em></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0.5in; margin-right:0in">&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),
(43, 'Citi by Satyam Bajpai', '09-28-17', 'akki', '1200px-Citi.svg.png', 'citi,interview,experience,internship', '<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">Company : Citi Corp</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">Job Location : Pune</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">CTC : 13.6 LPA</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">Round 1 :</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">MCQ (Aptitude &ndash; Quantitaive + Logical Reasoning + C C++ , Data Structures ,OS ,Networking ) . It was</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">easy and just required basic knowledge . Speed was a big factor .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">2 Coding Questions (1 hr) .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">40 LUCKY students were shortlisted . Maybe shortlisting was done on basis of MCQs only because some</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">people who did both codes were left behind . Even my code was 1 fully and 1 partially correct .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">Interviews were to be held in IIIT Allahabad .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">Technical Interview :</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">1. Tell me about yourself . I gave her brief description about myself , my areas of interest (DS , OS</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">and DBMS ) and my projects ( in Android ) .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">2. Draw ER diagram of database of your project .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">3. What was new in your project . Aren&rsquo;t these apps already there in market . I told her that one</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">app was part of tech fest and other I did for learning and getting deeper into android .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">4. Where did you get help for your project and was it a team or individual project ? I said individual</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">and told her about some good references .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">5. Draw Activity lifecycle in Android (Common question for people doing Android projects) .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">6. Given an array , find first missing positive number in O(n) time and O(1) space .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">7. Use case diagram for ATM machine .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">8. Difference between Method overloading and overriding and give an example .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">9. Why do you want to join Citi Corp ? I told her I&rsquo;ll get to work on different technologies , good</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">work culture and fast growth environment .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">17 were shortlisted for HR + Tech round .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">HR + Tech :</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">There were two interviewers : 1 HR and other Tech .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">1. How are you ? How has been the day today ? Tell about yourself .</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">2. What did you do in your project ? How did you implement this idea ?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">3. What is difference between client- server and normal application ?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">4. Do you know about web development ? What other technologies are you comfortable with ?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">I told him that I just have basic idea of web development and have never done a project in it . I</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">told him that I have worked in Java in Android and I would like to work on that .</span></span></span></p>\r\n');
